docs.abstract: The U.S. leads the free world in its helplessness before the dissolution of its most cherished values.
docs.snippet: The U.S. leads the free world in its helplessness before the dissolution of its most cherished values.
docs.lead_paragraph: MASHOBRA, India — “The world is going America’s way,” Fareed Zakaria wrote in 2008. “Countries are becoming more open, market friendly and democratic.” Since the fall of communism, American leaders in politics, business and journalism have repeatedly broadcast the conceit that we live, or will soon live, in the best of all possible worlds. Not even 9/11, the bloody stalemates in Iraq and Afghanistan or the worst economic crisis since the Depression challenged faith in a benignly Americanized world. Barack Obama declared last year that “if you had to choose any time in the course of human history to be alive, you’d choose this one. Right here in America, right now.”

docs.abstract: By making her pregnancy a dazzling performance, is the singer raising the bar too high?
docs.snippet: By making her pregnancy a dazzling performance, is the singer raising the bar too high?
docs.lead_paragraph: She may have dropped out of headlining Coachella this month because of her pregnancy, but Beyoncé has not dropped out of public life. Instead, she has swapped a festival stage for an Instagram stage, and so — just in time for what would have been her second concert performance — she released a performance of a different kind: a photo shoot showcasing not her songs but her stomach, framed by a batwing tunic, over-the-knee suede boots and mirrored glasses. Followed shortly thereafter by a white-gowned Easter extravaganza.

docs.abstract: A national movement for racial justice flared in the predominantly black Missouri city after a white police officer shot Michael Brown. But few people voted.
docs.snippet: A national movement for racial justice flared in the predominantly black Missouri city after a white police officer shot Michael Brown. But few people voted.
docs.lead_paragraph: FERGUSON, Mo. — When a national movement for racial justice flared here two and a half years ago, activists nationwide hoped to upend the political order. Ferguson was one of many predominantly black communities across the country that were under white control, and they strategized about ways to change that.

headline.main: Ferguson Re-Elects White Mayor 2 Years After Mike Brown Incident
headline.print_headline: Ferguson Voters Return a White Mayor to Office

docs.lead_paragraph: The phone rang in his study and Dwaine Perry answered with the weary resignation of a man who knew what was coming. The sun was setting on a late March evening as Mr. Perry listened to the voice on the other end of the line. “Go on,” he said, drooping his chin into his neck. Then came an extended pause, followed by a well-practiced recital of sympathies and condolences. “Well, I’ll get to work,” he finally said before hanging up. Time to plan another funeral.

docs.abstract: An exhibition at the New York Public Library’s Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture in Harlem chronicles the history of a dynamic movement.
docs.snippet: An exhibition at the New York Public Library’s Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture in Harlem chronicles the history of a dynamic movement.
docs.lead_paragraph: Given the economic, environmental and social policies emanating from the White House, the United States could be headed for its most dynamic era of public resistance since the 1960s, one for which the Women’s March last winter was just a warm-up. Such an era would demand fresh developments in political art, meaning art with a populist reach. Where will that come from?

headline.main: In ‘Black Power!,’ Art’s Political Punch and Populist Reach
